e some of the many questions posed here, in the new, expanded edition of Garnsey and Saller's pathbreaking account of the economy, society, and culture of the Roman Empire. This second edition includes a new introduction that explores the consequences for government and the governing classes of the replacement of the Republic by the rule of emperors. Addenda to the original chapters offer up-to-date discussions of issues and point to new evidence and approaches that have enlivened the study of Roman history in recent decades. A completely new chapter assesses how far Rome’s subjects resisted her hegemony. The bibliography has also been thoroughly updated, and a new color plate section has been added.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aancient europe.  aancient history.  aancient rome.  aancient society.  aclassical studies.  aclassical study.  aclassics.  aearly roman empire.  aeconomy of roman empire.  aenemies of rome.  afamilies in roman empire.  agreco roman history.  ahistory civilization.  ahistory of europe.  aprincipate era.  aroman culture and society.  aroman empire.  aroman history.  aroman imperialism.  aroman religion before christianity.  aroman society.  arome.  asocial hierarchy in roman empire.  athematic history of rome.  aworld history.1 aElsner, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, R. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaller, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWoolf, G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Compl